		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<div></div><p>The only issue I have with what Frodlin listed is I don't know what the actual dps ratio between knight/warrior would be if the high end weapons were modified by 1.6 like he asked for. I'd have to see some really controlled parses before ever jumping on board with any particular value (particularly as I strongly disagree with Frodlin's stated opinion that warriors should do up to 40% more melee dps than knights).</p><p>In addition, it brings up a concern with regard to the low end, as there is a plethora of 10/20-12/24 type ratio weapons, which would become as good or better than the like 2 high ratio knight one-handers I can think of at the newb level (talking no recommended/required levels here), both of which are expensive or rare or both. Considering the ratios on 2hers with no req/rec levels, that 1.6 mod would be way overpowered.</p><p>If it was *possible* to add such a mechanism to 1hers, if it was built in as something that only took affect at, oh, say level 50, or that scaled in levels from a lower value to the highest value at 70, might be more appropriate.</p><p>It also seems to me that just coding this in as a general feature (not warrior specific) would probably be easier, and they could just do away completely with knight specific 1hers (though I guess special code would have to go into preventing earlier knight 1hers from being modified thusly).</p><p>So basically, I have no problems with anything Frodlin said either, but before jumping on board with this kind of change, would like to see controlled parses or something so we can see what the effect actually is on relative dps, as well as considerations for other areas of the game.</p><p>----------</p><p>Most have stayed on target, those that haven't please stop with the back and forth as it merely leads to more derailment. What I have seen already shows that warriors and knights really aren't that far apart in what they think is fair, which is completely at odds with what you get from reading the other threads here. I really feel this kind of honest and measured discourse is much more likely to affect change than the bickering that has been going on.</p><p></p>	
